263
00:11:20,679 --> 00:11:24,415
in exchange
for backing Jessica.

264
00:11:24,483 --> 00:11:26,851
Well, you close him,
then we'll talk.

265
00:11:26,919 --> 00:11:28,853
That's not so reassuring.

266
00:11:28,921 --> 00:11:31,589
You came to me.

267
00:11:31,657 --> 00:11:34,125
I didn't come to you.

268
00:11:34,193 --> 00:11:35,660
I'll see you on the first tee.

269
00:11:35,728 --> 00:11:37,962
No, you won't.

270
00:11:38,030 --> 00:11:40,198
Oh, is this where
you make your threat?

271
00:11:40,266 --> 00:11:42,467
I've had the carrot,
now I get the stick?

272
00:11:42,535 --> 00:11:44,502
That's not my style.

273
00:11:44,570 --> 00:11:46,905
The person you're gonna meet
on the tee is Fred Couples.

274
00:11:46,972 --> 00:11:48,907
And just so we're clear,

275
00:11:48,974 --> 00:11:52,577
that's being closed
by Harvey Specter.

276
00:12:01,483 --> 00:12:03,070
Let's talk football.

277
00:12:03,095 --> 00:12:06,064
Peyton Manning goes down
you lose your first 13 games.

278
00:12:06,793 --> 00:12:09,178
You gotta protect your assets
and build for the future.

279
00:12:09,181 --> 00:12:10,681
You don't wanna pay
28 million for a guy

280
00:12:10,749 --> 00:12:12,283
who may not play next year.

281
00:12:12,351 --> 00:12:13,518
So what do you do?

282
00:12:13,585 --> 00:12:14,519
You move on.

283
00:12:14,586 --> 00:12:16,287
The season isn't over, Harvey.

284
00:12:16,355 --> 00:12:18,222
You're 200 million in the red

285
00:12:18,290 --> 00:12:20,558
with 1/4 billion due
in two days.

286
00:12:20,626 --> 00:12:24,228
Madison 25
is going to be built.

287
00:12:24,296 --> 00:12:28,266
Madison 25 should be built,
but the market's changed.

288
00:12:28,333 --> 00:12:30,268
Vacancies are up,
rents are down,

289
00:12:30,335 --> 00:12:31,936
and you can't take out
a loan against your future

290
00:12:32,004 --> 00:12:33,404
if the money's
never gonna flow.

291
00:12:33,472 --> 00:12:35,773
It's time to protect
your franchise.

292
00:12:35,841 --> 00:12:37,175
Really? I should just skate

293
00:12:37,242 --> 00:12:39,210
while the hundreds of
contractors and subcontractors

294
00:12:39,278 --> 00:12:41,312
that I've made financial
commitments to,

295
00:12:41,380 --> 00:12:43,614
they should just wait in line
with their hands held out,

296
00:12:43,682 --> 00:12:45,283
hoping for 50¢ on the dollar?

297
00:12:45,350 --> 00:12:47,919
They know how
the business works.

298
00:12:47,986 --> 00:12:50,321
Look, I know that Paul feels
I should protect myself.

299
00:12:50,389 --> 00:12:51,422
I should protect
my family business,

300
00:12:51,490 --> 00:12:54,358
but I want to protect
my family name.

301
00:12:54,426 --> 00:12:57,762
There's no shame
in declaring bankruptcy, okay?

302
00:12:57,830 --> 00:12:59,697
It's a tool that
will allow you to survive.

303
00:12:59,765 --> 00:13:02,066
Wanna know the kind of guy
I am, Harvey?

304
00:13:02,134 --> 00:13:04,068
I'm the kind of guy,

305
00:13:04,136 --> 00:13:07,705
that when the clock says,
"The game's over, take a knee,"

306
00:13:07,773 --> 00:13:09,707
that's when
I throw a hail Mary.

307
00:13:09,775 --> 00:13:12,877
Everybody throws a hail Mary
when they got nothing to lose.

308
00:13:12,945 --> 00:13:15,246
You got something to lose.

309
00:13:15,314 --> 00:13:16,881
I like long odds.

310
00:13:16,949 --> 00:13:19,884
Let's just say,
I won't declare bankruptcy.

311
00:13:19,952 --> 00:13:22,820
What are my other options?

312
00:13:22,888 --> 00:13:25,656
I have an idea.

313
00:13:36,068 --> 00:13:37,201
You were right...

314
00:13:37,269 --> 00:13:38,736
about Hardman and Jessica.

315
00:13:38,804 --> 00:13:42,440
- You want something from me.
- I do.

316
00:13:42,507 --> 00:13:44,909
Mike needs an extension
on a $1/4 billion loan.

317
00:13:44,977 --> 00:13:47,345
And you want me to believe
that you're here for Mike?

318
00:13:47,412 --> 00:13:48,446
Yes.

319
00:13:48,513 --> 00:13:50,615
- Mm-mm.
- Mm-mm.

320
00:13:50,682 --> 00:13:53,017
Harvey needs me.

321
00:13:53,085 --> 00:13:55,987
I know you're amazing
at dealing with banks, Louis.

322
00:13:56,054 --> 00:13:57,255
[Laughs] What, do you think

323
00:13:57,322 --> 00:13:59,023
I'm gonna fall for that shit?

324
00:13:59,091 --> 00:14:02,460
I mean just, like, the best.

325
00:14:05,764 --> 00:14:06,864
What bank?

326
00:14:06,932 --> 00:14:08,332
- National Metropolitan.
- The gatekeeper?

327
00:14:08,400 --> 00:14:11,535
Elaine Cohen?
[Chuckles] Exactly.

328
00:14:11,603 --> 00:14:14,438
So, you think
you can get him in?

329
00:14:14,506 --> 00:14:17,541
Well, you know
I can get him in.

330
00:14:17,609 --> 00:14:20,444
But you also know
I can keep him out.

331
00:14:20,512 --> 00:14:21,979
Okay, what's it gonna take?

332
00:14:22,047 --> 00:14:23,614
Five details
of the Pearson Hardman divide.

333
00:14:23,682 --> 00:14:25,116
- No. No.
- Three? One?

334
00:14:25,183 --> 00:14:28,452
One.

335
00:14:28,520 --> 00:14:30,809
And I get the Albee tickets.

336
00:14:32,294 --> 00:14:33,983
We get the Albee tickets.

337
00:14:38,864 --> 00:14:40,131
Tell a soul, deal's off.

338
00:14:40,198 --> 00:14:41,798
Done.

339
00:14:45,404 --> 00:14:46,804
I love Tom.

340
00:14:46,872 --> 00:14:48,706
I love Madison 25, really.

341
00:14:48,774 --> 00:14:50,541
But I'm afraid if you look
at the fine print,

342
00:14:50,609 --> 00:14:52,209
the terms of the loan
are what they are,

343
00:14:52,277 --> 00:14:53,577
and what they aren't

344
00:14:53,645 --> 00:14:55,947
is subject to renegotiation.
Are you kidding me?

345
00:14:56,014 --> 00:14:58,015
The terms of loans
are adjusted all the time.

346
00:14:58,083 --> 00:15:00,084
And you can see
he has the assets.

347
00:15:00,152 --> 00:15:02,253
What I see?

348
00:15:02,321 --> 00:15:06,624
Is that I'm gonna have to give
you a 50% haircut on that.

349
00:15:06,692 --> 00:15:07,959
That is not liquid.

350
00:15:08,026 --> 00:15:10,127
You're never gonna
be able to sell

351
00:15:10,195 --> 00:15:12,630
a minority partnership interest,
and that...

352
00:15:12,698 --> 00:15:14,699
a monkey could tell
you could never monetize that.

353
00:15:14,766 --> 00:15:16,467
You know what else
a monkey could tell you?

354
00:15:16,535 --> 00:15:20,071
You're about to ruin a property
that will make you millions.

355
00:15:20,138 --> 00:15:22,673
I'm so sorry, gentlemen,
but this is not 2007.

356
00:15:22,741 --> 00:15:25,076
We don't play that game
anymore.

357
00:15:25,143 --> 00:15:27,345
The days of you
high-flying people

358
00:15:27,412 --> 00:15:29,113
claiming you're richer than God

359
00:15:29,181 --> 00:15:31,849
when all you're really doing is
moving assets around are over.

360
00:15:31,917 --> 00:15:33,217
Today we're gonna take
a look up your skirt

361
00:15:33,285 --> 00:15:34,752
and see what you have.

362
00:15:34,820 --> 00:15:39,390
And I'm afraid
you don't have much.

363
00:15:41,793 --> 00:15:42,793
- She actually said that?
- Yes.

364
00:15:42,861 --> 00:15:43,995
Please don't make me relive it.

365
00:15:44,062 --> 00:15:46,897
As it is, I may drink a lot
on our date.

366
00:15:46,965 --> 00:15:50,301
You know,
if we're really gonna do this,

367
00:15:50,369 --> 00:15:53,938
we should probably be careful
talking about it here.

368
00:15:54,006 --> 00:15:55,740
Oh, you're right. Yeah.

369
00:15:55,807 --> 00:15:58,142
We should definitely set some
dating ground rules.

370
00:15:58,210 --> 00:15:59,643
You're not taking me home,
to my place or yours.

371
00:15:59,711 --> 00:16:04,048
Whoa, okay, I'm not talking
about ground rules for sex.

372
00:16:04,116 --> 00:16:07,284
I'm talking about ground rules
for keeping this thing quiet.

373
00:16:07,352 --> 00:16:11,122
Oh. So you think if we went
to my place or yours,

374
00:16:11,189 --> 00:16:14,025
that means sex?

375
00:16:14,092 --> 00:16:17,294
Uh, no. I mean...

376
00:16:17,362 --> 00:16:19,063
you... [Laughs]

377
00:16:19,131 --> 00:16:20,564
Uh... [Clears throat]

378
00:16:20,632 --> 00:16:23,067
What I meant was that I know you
didn't want to date anyone

379
00:16:23,135 --> 00:16:26,470
in the office, and I assume you
have a reason for that.

380
00:16:26,538 --> 00:16:27,671
Oh, okay, there is.

381
00:16:27,739 --> 00:16:30,241
There's a story.
I see it right there.

382
00:16:30,308 --> 00:16:31,375
There's no story there.
I dated someone here once.

383
00:16:31,443 --> 00:16:33,044
It didn't work out. That's it.

384
00:16:33,111 --> 00:16:35,379
No more questions.
Those are my ground rules.

385
00:16:35,447 --> 00:16:38,315
Hmm, note to self:
Touchy about dating history.

386
00:16:38,383 --> 00:16:40,251
Wow, I smell pheromones
in the air.

387
00:16:40,318 --> 00:16:44,622
Which suggests to me, Ms. Zane,
that you failed to grasp

388
00:16:44,689 --> 00:16:46,490
the importance of the task
that I assigned.

389
00:16:46,558 --> 00:16:47,725
Or unless you're done.

390
00:16:47,793 --> 00:16:48,726
- Well, I...
- No?

391
00:16:48,794 --> 00:16:50,227
You do realize you asked her

392
00:16:50,295 --> 00:16:53,230
to summarize every case
in the firm, right?

393
00:16:53,298 --> 00:16:55,332
I'm so sorry,
was I talking to you?

394
00:16:55,400 --> 00:16:57,568
Because I already
did your job for you.

395
00:16:57,636 --> 00:17:00,037
Actually,
the bank didn't budge.

396
00:17:00,105 --> 00:17:02,573
I got you in, Michael.

397
00:17:02,641 --> 00:17:05,309
What, do you expect me
to do everything?

398
00:17:05,377 --> 00:17:08,112
Now, do I have to gather
every first year

399
00:17:08,180 --> 00:17:10,548
and make them stay the night
because the paralegal

400
00:17:10,615 --> 00:17:12,550
was too busy flirting
and couldn't get it done?

401
00:17:12,617 --> 00:17:17,154
Actually, all the associates
are leaving early tonight.

402
00:17:17,222 --> 00:17:18,589
Excuse me?

403
00:17:18,657 --> 00:17:22,259
Yeah, Hardman invited everyone
to his box at the Garden.

404
00:17:22,327 --> 00:17:25,296
Springsteen.

405
00:17:25,363 --> 00:17:27,498
The boss?

406
00:17:27,566 --> 00:17:31,635
Wait, didn't he invite you?

407
00:17:34,339 --> 00:17:35,573
You think I want to spend
my evening with a bunch of

408
00:17:35,640 --> 00:17:37,041
douche bag associates
at a concert

409
00:17:37,109 --> 00:17:40,244
given by a goddamn
octogenarian?

410
00:17:40,312 --> 00:17:42,613
Get it done.

411
00:17:54,793 --> 00:17:57,695
If I wanted to sink his
business to keep his business,

412
00:17:57,762 --> 00:17:59,597
I could have done that myself.

413
00:17:59,664 --> 00:18:02,133
Hello, Paul.
Make yourself at home.

414
00:18:02,200 --> 00:18:05,035
You made him think he could
risk, not just this project,

415
00:18:05,103 --> 00:18:08,372
but everything he owns,
on a personal guarantee.

416
00:18:08,440 --> 00:18:10,941
Are you crazy? What I am, Paul,

417
00:18:11,009 --> 00:18:15,045
is working my ass off
to make your client happy.

418
00:18:15,113 --> 00:18:17,615
You think I haven't
tried everything

419
00:18:17,682 --> 00:18:19,817
to keep his dream alive?

420
00:18:19,885 --> 00:18:21,819
The fact is, the bank
is going to foreclose.

421
00:18:21,887 --> 00:18:23,053
Tom needs to be protected,

422
00:18:23,121 --> 00:18:26,090
and your plan
is too big a risk.

423
00:18:26,158 --> 00:18:27,158
For you, yes, but not for Tom,

424
00:18:27,225 --> 00:18:28,792
and as I understand it,
we work for him.

425
00:18:28,860 --> 00:18:29,894
[Laughing] No, no, no, no.

426
00:18:29,961 --> 00:18:32,163
I work for him.

427
00:18:32,230 --> 00:18:34,231
You are working for me.

428
00:18:34,299 --> 00:18:35,966
I said he needed
to declare bankruptcy,

429
00:18:36,034 --> 00:18:40,004
but, oh, you...
you played it your way.

430
00:18:40,071 --> 00:18:44,508
Well, Jessica may give
you free rein to do that,

431
00:18:44,576 --> 00:18:46,977
but I can't imagine
Hardman will.

432
00:18:47,045 --> 00:18:51,649
You know, Paul, couples passed
on a little tip for you.

433
00:18:51,716 --> 00:18:55,085
He said your game was weak
because you were too cautious.

434
00:18:55,153 --> 00:18:58,522
I said, "It's not your game,
it's who you are."

435
00:19:05,664 --> 00:19:11,535
Harvey, I may have been
knocked down to the 46th floor,

436
00:19:11,603 --> 00:19:13,671
but bankruptcy

437
00:19:13,738 --> 00:19:19,276
is on the rise.

438
00:19:19,344 --> 00:19:24,381
My influence in this firm
is not nothing.

439
00:19:28,687 --> 00:19:31,322
You get Tom
to sign those papers.

440
00:19:31,389 --> 00:19:36,193
Is that a threat?

441
00:19:36,261 --> 00:19:38,162
I don't make threats.

442
00:19:38,230 --> 00:19:42,099
I just do what I do.

443
00:19:58,390 --> 00:19:59,723
You find anything?

444
00:19:59,791 --> 00:20:01,592
Oh, I'm gonna make
Paul love you.

445
00:20:01,660 --> 00:20:03,727
That's doubtful. He got wind
of our little maneuver.

446
00:20:03,795 --> 00:20:04,895
- [Laughs]
- What?

447
00:20:04,963 --> 00:20:06,897
You said "got wind."

448
00:20:06,965 --> 00:20:09,667
[Clears throat] Anyway,
I have another maneuver.

449
00:20:09,734 --> 00:20:10,901
A better one.

450
00:20:10,969 --> 00:20:12,903
Paul says we tell Tom
there's no other way.

451
00:20:12,971 --> 00:20:14,271
But there is another way.

452
00:20:14,339 --> 00:20:15,539
Oh, wait, you don't even want
to hear it?

453
00:20:15,607 --> 00:20:16,941
Of course I want to hear it.

454
00:20:17,008 --> 00:20:19,643
Since when do I take marching
orders from a bow tie?

455
00:20:19,711 --> 00:20:20,778
There are eight projects
being built

456
00:20:20,845 --> 00:20:22,746
in the two blocks
around Madison 25.

457
00:20:22,814 --> 00:20:24,481
Every one of them
started after it.

458
00:20:24,549 --> 00:20:26,717
Madison 25 is the centerpiece
of the whole development.

459
00:20:26,785 --> 00:20:28,886
If it's not finished,
they're all worthless.

460
00:20:28,954 --> 00:20:30,821
That's not the bank's problem.

461
00:20:30,889 --> 00:20:33,624
But it is, 'cause guess
what six of these buildings

462
00:20:33,692 --> 00:20:37,628
have in common.

463
00:20:37,696 --> 00:20:39,396
National's backing them all?

464
00:20:39,464 --> 00:20:42,233
Doesn't make sense for them
to foreclose and devalue

465
00:20:42,300 --> 00:20:43,267
all their other projects.

466
00:20:43,335 --> 00:20:45,236
Unless they have
another agenda.

467
00:20:45,303 --> 00:20:50,007
Huh, I wonder where we could
ever find evidence of that?

468
00:20:50,075 --> 00:20:52,309
Think that helps us?

469
00:20:52,377 --> 00:20:54,178
I think we can take this
to the bank.

470
00:20:54,246 --> 00:20:55,379
Now, you see, that's funny

471
00:20:55,447 --> 00:20:56,914
because we're actually going
to a bank.

472
00:20:56,982 --> 00:21:00,951
That's good.

473
00:21:04,823 --> 00:21:07,224
Twice in one day, Mr. Specter.

474
00:21:07,292 --> 00:21:09,193
I understand how
your client must feel.

475
00:21:09,261 --> 00:21:10,828
Actually,
he's feeling fantastic.

476
00:21:10,895 --> 00:21:12,296
You know why that is?

477
00:21:12,364 --> 00:21:15,366
'Cause I told him the balloon
payment's going away.

478
00:21:15,433 --> 00:21:18,836
Okay, I'll bite.
Why is it going away?

479
00:21:18,903 --> 00:21:20,204
Because as much
as people hate lawyers,

480
00:21:20,272 --> 00:21:22,106
you know who they hate more?
Bankers.

481
00:21:22,173 --> 00:21:23,941
After all, you were the ones

482
00:21:24,009 --> 00:21:25,909
that got us into this recession
in the first place, right?

483
00:21:25,977 --> 00:21:28,912
Oh, gentlemen.
I do not need a history lesson.

484
00:21:28,980 --> 00:21:30,681
Then let's talk
about the future.

485
00:21:30,749 --> 00:21:33,951
What happens to Madison 25 after
you force it into bankruptcy?

486
00:21:34,019 --> 00:21:36,520
Maybe someone steps in
and finishes it.

487
00:21:36,588 --> 00:21:38,222
Someone whose recent
merger leaves them

488
00:21:38,290 --> 00:21:40,357
needing a large
downtown address?

489
00:21:40,425 --> 00:21:41,692
Oh, now that you mention it,

490
00:21:41,760 --> 00:21:43,527
there's a little item
in your shareholder letter

491
00:21:43,595 --> 00:21:46,030
about the search for
a new corporate headquarters.

492
00:21:46,097 --> 00:21:48,532
- Yeah, I like to read.
- Well, I don't...

493
00:21:48,600 --> 00:21:50,267
You intend to leverage
this foreclosure

494
00:21:50,335 --> 00:21:52,469
to get a prime piece
of real estate at a song.

495
00:21:52,537 --> 00:21:55,706
You see, Elaine,
we looked up your skirt.

496
00:21:55,774 --> 00:21:57,074
And the six clients
you represent

497
00:21:57,142 --> 00:21:59,209
surrounding Madison 25...
well, it turns out

498
00:21:59,277 --> 00:22:01,312
Pearson Hardman actually
reps three of them.

499
00:22:01,379 --> 00:22:03,580
And when the other three find
out about what you've done,

500
00:22:03,648 --> 00:22:05,282
which will happen right after
I leave here,

501
00:22:05,350 --> 00:22:06,884
we'll rep all six.

502
00:22:06,951 --> 00:22:09,119
And when we move
their business elsewhere,

503
00:22:09,187 --> 00:22:11,955
they'll take roughly, mm...

504
00:22:12,023 --> 00:22:14,358
Mm, a shitload of money
out of your bank.

505
00:22:14,426 --> 00:22:17,328
- Shitload?
- Well, give or take.

506
00:22:22,467 --> 00:22:25,669
It's important that nobody
knows about this.

507
00:22:25,737 --> 00:22:28,072
I've never...

508
00:22:28,139 --> 00:22:31,275
done anything like this before.

509
00:22:31,343 --> 00:22:35,045
Louis, there's nothing
to be ashamed of.

510
00:22:35,113 --> 00:22:36,714
Exploring your options
is something

511
00:22:36,781 --> 00:22:39,650
everybody does these days.

512
00:22:39,718 --> 00:22:41,485
Sometimes you're
in a relationship,

513
00:22:41,553 --> 00:22:43,454
they take you for granted.

514
00:22:43,521 --> 00:22:46,657
